MODULE  request@2.88.2   (the deprecated HTTP client — verified-recompose of the PURE core)
SRC     npm:request@2.88.2  lib/*.js   (Apache-2.0; npm-deprecated 2020-02)
ABOUT   A big, effectful library. The SIR firewall carves a thin PURE helper layer out of a large
        HTTP EFFECT spine. This package verifies the FUNCTIONAL leaves against held-out oracles
        stamped from the real original; the EFFECT spine is declared here and is trace-oracle work.

# ── the firewall ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FIREWALL  FUNCTIONAL ⊅ EFFECT
  pure    (FUNCTIONAL):  lib/helpers.js — paramsHaveRequestBody, toBase64, copy, isReadStream
  suspect (FUNCTIONAL?): lib/helpers.js — md5 (OPAQUE node:crypto), safeStringify (OPAQUE json-stringify-safe)
  shell   (EFFECT):      lib/request.js (http(s).request EMIT / response REQUEST), lib/redirect.js (net),
                         lib/cookies.js (STATE jar), lib/oauth.js/hawk.js/har.js (crypto/sign),
                         lib/multipart.js/tunnel.js (io/net), helpers.version (reads process.version =
                         ambient), helpers.defer (setImmediate/nextTick = scheduling),
                         auth.basic/bearer (mutate `this` + emit 'error' — a PURE header core wrapped
                         in an EFFECT method)

# ── verified units (this package — pure leaves + the first EFFECT leaf) ───────
UNITS
  FUNCTIONAL  paramsHaveRequestBody  helpers.js:paramsHaveRequestBody   [leaf]
  FUNCTIONAL  toBase64               helpers.js:toBase64                [leaf, Buffer]
  EFFECT      getProxyFromURI        getProxyFromURI.js                 [leaf, env boundary — INJECTED, record/replay]

# ── the EFFECT surface the trace oracle must pin (NOT covered here yet) ────────
SURFACE
  env boundary  (REQUEST env.read):   COVERED — getProxyFromURI verified by injection / record-replay
                                      (set the env snapshot, run, compare; the inbound half of the trace).
  outbound (EMIT, recorded):          net.write (http/https request bytes) ; redirect follow   — FRONTIER
  inbound  (REQUEST, injected):       net.read (response) ; fs.read (multipart file bodies) ;
                                      time (date headers) ; rand (multipart boundary / uuid)  — FRONTIER
  => the ENV boundary is done; the NET/HTTP EMIT trace (the actual send: emit request bytes, inject
     response, order-sensitive) is the remaining frontier (the dotenv/editorconfig EFFECT-tier precedent).
     Today: pure core + the env-effect leaf — honestly partial, and one boundary class deeper than before.

NOTES
  - request is npm-DEPRECATED (2020) yet still load-bearing in countless dependency trees — a prime
    re-derive target: pin its behavior, own your build, stop trusting an unmaintained publisher.
  - the leaves verified here are request's OWN helpers (lib/helpers.js), not its dependencies.
